answers.body_markdown:
The `MyTask` instance is created manually (in `MyTask th = new MyTask()`) and not by Spring, hence dependency injection will not be performed and the autowired  `JobLauncher` will be null.

You need to create a bean of type `MyTask` (so that its dependencies are correctly injected) then inject it in your `Scheduler` class as a collaborator.

As a side note, this is not the ideal way to launch multiple jobs concurrently. You are creating a `JobLauncher` per thread, which in turn uses a `SyncTaskExecutor` by default. What you can do is create a single `JobLauncher` and configure it with a pool of threads to launch jobs concurrently, something like:

    @Bean
    public JobLauncher jobLauncher() {
	   SimpleJobLauncher jobLauncher = new SimpleJobLauncher();
	   jobLauncher.setJobRepository(jobRepository());
	   jobLauncher.setTaskExecutor(new SimpleAsyncTaskExecutor()); // or use ThreadPoolTaskExecutor
	   jobLauncher.afterPropertiesSet();
	   return jobLauncher;
    }

You can find more details in the [Configuring a JobLauncher](https://docs.spring.io/spring-batch/4.2.x/reference/html/job.html#configuringJobLauncher) section of the reference documentation.

